1. FizzBuzz rules and algorithmic patterns
- Core rules: iterate sequentially over integers from 1 to N inclusive.
- For each integer i: if divisible by both 3 and 5 output "FizzBuzz"; else if divisible by 3 output "Fizz"; else if divisible by 5 output "Buzz"; else output the integer.
- Divisibility detection: use modulo arithmetic: i % 3 === 0, i % 5 === 0. Detect both via i % 15 === 0 or by checking both booleans and concatenating results.
- Complexity: time O(N), space O(1) if streaming output, O(N) if collecting results in array.
- Implementation patterns: return an array of length N with values drawn from the rules; provide an option to stream/print to console; prefer checking combined condition first (i % 15 === 0) to avoid overriding.
- Edge behaviors: define behavior for N <= 0 (usually return empty array), non-integer N (validate and reject), very large N (protect against memory exhaustion when collecting results). Provide configuration options: start (default 1), end (N), step (default 1).

2. Input validation and error handling
- Use Number.isInteger(value) to assert integer inputs. Signature: Number.isInteger(value) -> boolean. Returns false for NaN, Infinity, non-number values. Returns true for numeric values that are mathematically integers within floating-point precision limits.
- For type mismatches: throw new TypeError(message) where message describes expected type. TypeError constructor: TypeError([message]) -> TypeError instance; instance.name === "TypeError".
- For out-of-range values (e.g., negative end, end < start, or excessively large N if rejecting): throw new RangeError(message). RangeError constructor: RangeError([message]) -> RangeError instance; use to signal argument outside allowed numeric range.
- Example validation rules (implementation-ready):
  - if (!Number.isInteger(end)) throw new TypeError('end must be integer');
  - if (end < 1) throw new RangeError('end must be >= 1');
  - if (end - start > MAX_SAFE_ITERATIONS) throw new RangeError('range too large');
- Recommended constant: MAX_SAFE_ITERATIONS = 1_000_000 by default for collector mode; streaming mode may allow larger ranges.

3. JavaScript module export patterns
- Named export syntax (explicit): export function foo() { } ; export const VALUE = 1; export { foo, VALUE }.
- Default export syntax: export default expression; export default function name() { } ; only one default per module.
- Re-export/aggregation: export { name } from 'module'; export * from 'module' re-exports all named exports (does not re-export default); export * as ns from 'module' to expose module namespace.
- Use cases for packaging fizz-buzz utilities: export a default convenience function that runs FizzBuzz and named exports for helpers (isFizz, isBuzz, formatValue). Example export surface: export default runFizzBuzz; export { isFizz, isBuzz, formatValue }.
- Module execution: export declarations are static and evaluated as module declarations; do not rely on run-time mutation of exported bindings for API shape.

4. Node.js ESM runtime rules and packaging
- Enabling ESM in Node.js: set package.json "type": "module" to make .js files be interpreted as ES modules; alternatively use .mjs file extension or --input-type=module for one-off evaluation.
- Mandatory file extensions: relative/absolute import specifiers must include file extensions (e.g. import { x } from './mod.js'); directory indexes must be fully specified (./dir/index.js must be written with filename).
- Specifier types:
  - relative specifiers: './x.js' or '../x.mjs' (file extension required)
  - bare specifiers: 'pkg' or 'pkg/sub' resolved via package resolution (subject to package.json "exports" map)
  - absolute file: file:///...
- import.meta properties (Node.js specifics): import.meta.url -> file: URL of current module; import.meta.filename -> absolute path string of current module (Node >= v21/v20 as stable); import.meta.dirname -> directory name of current module (string). Caveat: some import.meta properties only available for file: modules.
- Import attributes and JSON modules: import foo from './data.json' with { type: 'json' }; Node supports type: 'json' for import with attribute.
- Built-in module imports with node: prefix: import fs from 'node:fs' or import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises'; prefer node: prefix to avoid ambiguity.

